29,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2017-03-21T05:41:29.000Z","msg":"<blockquote><blockquote><blockquote>Dse level I guess <br />\n<br />\n你解唔解釋到ppl with Down syndrome 做mitotic cell division時候:<br />\n<br />\nAn extra 21st chromosome will line up with other two chromosomes to form one chromosome - homologous chromosome<br />\nll ll ll 21st<br />\n<br />\nOr<br />\n<br />\nAn extra chromosome will be left unpaired as a &quot;24th&quot; chromosome <br />\nll ll 21st - a pair of homologous chromosomes <br />\n..<br />\n<br />\nll &quot;24th&quot; chromosome left unpaired <br />\n<br />\nThanks</blockquote><br />\nMeiotic cell division *<br />\n更正for typo</blockquote><br />\n一定唔係dse level <img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/sosad.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /> <br />\n<br />\n可能同cytokine regulating cell cycle 有關?<br />\n<br />\n利申: 唔識</blockquote><br />\nThanks <br />\n因為我用現有dse既知識推唔到答案..<br />\n<br />\nMendel law conclude a pair of hereditary factors (正常情況下，由結果，已發生結果反推）<br />\nModern genetics 都係補充番正常情況係點<br />\n<br />\n但呢種特別例子，一來用Mendel law既conclusion根本就不對題，因為佢既理論由一定有a pair of hereditary factors + 一定發生既結果作出發點，根本解釋唔到出發點以外既情況<br />\n<br />\n二來dse modern genetic 一樣assume左a pair of homologous chromosome<br />\n<br />\n所以我問問你"},{"pid":"d97ccac0e5f90341fded2937d9f876dd4eb9460f","tid":163930,"uid":24623,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2017-03-21T06:14:24.000Z","msg":"<blockquote>可唔可以outline下Renin-Angiotensin-Aldosterone axis點樣regulate blood pressure<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/adore.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /> <br />\n<br />\n利申學過 但唔記得</blockquote><br />\n<br />\nBlood pressure decrease: Juxtaglomerular cells release renin in response to GFR decrease<br />\n<br />\nRenin --&gt; Angiotensin I --&gt; Angiotensin II --&gt; Aldosterone <br />\n<br />\nAngiotensin II causes vasoconstriction: increase BP <br />\nAldosterone activates more basolareral Na/K-ATPase: Increase water reabsoption in kidney--&gt; increase BP<br />\n<br />\n大致上係咁?"},{"pid":"5eea820298bcf57f197ff11579b667b2ff25f355","tid":163930,"uid":3980,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2017-03-21T06:14:48.000Z","msg":"Human abnormalities in chromosome number are influ- enced by the age of the parents. Older parents are more likely to produce children with abnormalities in chromosome number. Down syndrome provides an example. The common form of this disorder is caused by the inheritance of three copies of chromo- some 21. The incidence of Down syndrome rises with the age of either parent. In males, however, the rise occurs relatively late in life, usually past the age when most men have children. By com- parison, the likelihood of having a child with Down syndrome rises dramatically during a woman&rsquo;s reproductive age (Figure 8.17). This syndrome was first described by the English physician John Langdon Down in 1866. The association between maternal age and Down syndrome was later discovered by L. S. Penrose in 1933, even before the chromosomal basis for the disorder was identified by the French scientist J&eacute;r&ocirc;me Lejeune in 1959.<br />\n<br />\nDown syndrome is most commonly caused by nondisjunction, which means that the chromosomes do not segregate properly. (Non- disjunction is discussed later in this chapter.) In this case, non- disjunction of chromosome 21 most commonly occurs during meiosis I in the oocyte.<br />\nDifferent hypotheses have been proposed to explain the relationship between maternal age and Down syndrome. One popular idea suggests that it may be due to the age of the oocytes. Human primary oocytes are produced within the ovary of the female fetus prior to birth and are arrested at prophase of meiosis I and remain in this stage until the time of ovulation. Therefore, as a woman ages, her primary oocytes have been in prophase I for a progressively longer period of time. This added length of time may contribute to an increased frequency of non- disjunction. About 5% of the time, Down syndrome is due to an extra paternal chromosome. Prenatal tests can determine if a fetus has Down syndrome and some other genetic abnormalities. The topic of genetic testing is discussed in Chapter 22.<br />\n<br />\n<br />\nsor太長 我喺genetics textbk quote出嚟 其實我完全唔識<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/sosad.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"68df771b18d2cccc003ab3c727309f6009535ea2","tid":163930,"uid":24623,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2017-03-21T06:17:46.000Z","msg":"<blockquote><blockquote><blockquote><blockquote>Dse level I guess <br />\n<br />\n你解唔解釋到ppl with Down syndrome 做mitotic cell division時候:<br />\n<br />\nAn extra 21st chromosome will line up with other two chromosomes to form one chromosome - homologous chromosome<br />\nll ll ll 21st<br />\n<br />\nOr<br />\n<br />\nAn extra chromosome will be left unpaired as a &quot;24th&quot; chromosome <br />\nll ll 21st - a pair of homologous chromosomes <br />\n..<br />\n<br />\nll &quot;24th&quot; chromosome left unpaired <br />\n<br />\nThanks</blockquote><br />\nMeiotic cell division *<br />\n更正for typo</blockquote><br />\n一定唔係dse level <img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/sosad.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /> <br />\n<br />\n可能同cytokine regulating cell cycle 有關?<br />\n<br />\n利申: 唔識</blockquote><br />\nThanks <br />\n因為我用現有dse既知識推唔到答案..<br />\n<br />\nMendel law conclude a pair of hereditary factors (正常情況下，由結果，已發生結果反推）<br />\nModern genetics 都係補充番正常情況係點<br />\n<br />\n但呢種特別例子，一來用Mendel law既conclusion根本就不對題，因為佢既理論由一定有a pair of hereditary factors + 一定發生既結果作出發點，根本解釋唔到出發點以外既情況<br />\n<br />\n二來dse modern genetic 一樣assume左a pair of homologous chromosome<br />\n<br />\n所以我問問你</blockquote><br />\n<br />\nDSE嘅Bio實在係太片面，好多野都冇比explanation，考操卷答題記keyword多過知識層面嘅野，巴打考完入U繼續研究啦<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/sosad.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"}]}